  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Graph Theory: What does it mean if vertices are adjacent?",
  "response": "In **graph theory**, the concept of **adjacency** is fundamental to understanding the structure and relationships within a graph. Here's a comprehensive explanation of what it means for vertices to be adjacent:\n\n### **Definition of Adjacent Vertices**\n\n**Adjacent vertices** (or **neighbors**) are two vertices in a graph that are **directly connected by an edge**. In other words, if there is an edge **E** that links vertex **A** to vertex **B**, then **A** and **B** are considered adjacent.\n\n### **Types of Graphs and Adjacency**\n\n1. **Undirected Graphs**:\n   - In an **undirected graph**, edges have no orientation. This means the edge **{A, B}** is identical to **{B, A}**.\n   - **Adjacency** is mutual; if **A** is adjacent to **B**, then **B** is also adjacent to **A**.\n\n   *Example*:\n   ```\n   A -- B\n   ```\n   Here, **A** and **B** are adjacent.\n\n2. **Directed Graphs (Digraphs)**:\n   - In a **directed graph**, edges have a direction, indicated by an arrow from one vertex to another.\n   - **Adjacency** can be **asymmetric**:\n     - If there is an edge from **A** to **B** (denoted as **A \u2192 B**), then **A** is adjacent to **B**.\n     - However, **B** is not necessarily adjacent to **A** unless there is a separate edge **B \u2192 A**.\n\n   *Example*:\n   ```\n   A \u2192 B\n   ```\n   Here, **A** is adjacent to **B**, but **B** is not adjacent to **A** unless an edge **B \u2192 A** exists.\n\n### **Adjacency in Adjacency Matrices**\n\nAn **adjacency matrix** is a way to represent a graph using a square matrix. The element **M[i][j]** in the matrix indicates whether there is an edge from vertex **i** to vertex **j**.\n\n- **Undirected Graphs**: The adjacency matrix is **symmetric** because if **A** is adjacent to **B**, then **B** is adjacent to **A**.\n- **Directed Graphs**: The adjacency matrix may be **asymmetric**, reflecting the direction of edges.\n\n**Example**:\nConsider an undirected graph with vertices **A**, **B**, and **C** where **A** is adjacent to **B** and **A** is adjacent to **C**.\n\nThe adjacency matrix would be:\n```\n   A B C\nA [0 1 1]\nB [1 0 0]\nC [1 0 0]\n```\nHere, **1** indicates adjacency, and **0** indicates no direct connection.\n\n### **Importance of Adjacency**\n\n- **Graph Traversal**: Understanding adjacency is crucial for algorithms that traverse graphs, such as Depth-First Search (DFS) and Breadth-First Search (BFS).\n- **Pathfinding**: Determining adjacent vertices helps in finding paths between nodes.\n- **Network Analysis**: In social networks, adjacency reveals direct relationships or connections between individuals.\n\n### **Summary**\n\n- **Adjacent Vertices**: Two vertices connected directly by an edge.\n- **Undirected Graphs**: Adjacency is mutual.\n- **Directed Graphs**: Adjacency is directional.\n- **Adjacency Matrix**: A mathematical representation to depict adjacency between vertices.\n\nUnderstanding adjacency is essential for analyzing and solving various problems in graph theory, from routing and networking to social dynamics and beyond.",
